Refresh the page and see the count increase.

5.Let's clean up the resources created in the previous steps.
Delete the redis and clickcounter containers, alongwith the clicknet network you had created.

To stop and delete the containers:
docker rm -f redis
docker rm -f clickcounter
To delete the network:
docker network rm clicknet


root@docker-host ~ ➜  docker rm -f redis
redis

root@docker-host ~ ➜  docker rm -f clickcounter
clickcounter

root@docker-host ~ ➜  docker network rm clicknet
clicknet

6.You saw how we first created a Docker network and then attached our containers to it.
Docker Compose simplifies this entire process by allowing us to define multiple containers, networks, ports, and environment variables inside a single compose.yaml file.
We will see this in action in the next task.

7.Create a compose.yaml file in the /root/clickcounter directory. Once done, bring up the stack using Docker Compose.
The compose file should have the following exact specification:
1. redis service - Use redis:alpine image name
2. clickcounter service - Use the kodekloud/click-counter image name; the app runs on port 5000 and should be exposed on host port 8085.

First, move to the clickcounter directory:
cd /root/clickcounter
Use the below compose file:
services:
  redis:
    image: redis:alpine
  clickcounter:
    image: kodekloud/click-counter
    ports:
    - 8085:5000
Then run the docker compose up -d command.
The -d flag has been added to run the containers in the background.

root@docker-host ~ ➜  cd /root/clickcounter

root@docker-host ~/clickcounter ➜  vi compose.yaml

root@docker-host ~/clickcounter ➜  docker compose up -d
